The SS Monte Carlo shipwreck is once again exposed on Coronado Beach, thanks to the recent storms and large surf - Coronado Landscape Photography

"Thanks to the recent storms and large surf the SS Monte Carlo shipwreck is once again exposed on Coronado Beach. For those unfamiliar with the shipwreck, the Monte Carlo was a gambling ship that traveled international waters off the coast of Coronado to avoid state and federal jurisdiction. During a storm on New Year's Day in 1937 the anchored ship drifted onto the beach in front of what is now the Coronado Shores condos. Because of the illegal activities that took place on the ship, no one claimed ownership and it was grounded for good. Some believe there is still treasure hidden inside the wreckage. The shipwreck can currently be viewed at low tide, until the surf slowly covers it with sand once again."

After further investigation on our end, while not SDG&E employees, we have determined that the two individuals in question were employees of a contractor working for SDG&E. The project includes site visits to customer gas meters to collect information and multi-meter readings.

A month ago this bobcat was suffering from a fractured paw and was quite emaciated. Today, the cat has a clean bill of health and was released back in to the Cleveland National Forest outside of Descanso.

You'll see more of the bobcat tonight at 5 and hear from the rescuers, who explain why they're seeing more and more wild animals creeping closer to populated areas.

Read about their emotional journey through this brave act: http://bit.ly/1lntf7f and SHARE their story with others.

"The only reason I'm here is to tell his story to try and stop this from happening again," he tells Barbara.

Story: http://bit.ly/SguQ7g

It was 70 years ago today that 160,000 Allied troops stormed the beaches of Nazi-occupied France at Normandy, in one of the most momentous events in world history.

"It was like opening the door and stepping into hell. It was horrific — and the screams, and the people dying," one veteran recalls. They were dying all over the beach." 

Story: http://bit.ly/1kQ4eRt

How well do you know your history?

Did you know that tomorrow marks the 70th anniversary of D-Day? On June 6, 1944, under a cloud of secrecy, enough people to overflow the nation's largest college football stadiums stormed five French beaches to gain a crucial foothold in the Nazi-occupied country. http://bit.ly/SzZ7i3

D-Day was a long time ago but many lives were lost. Share this with your friends so those who died -- and the remaining living survivors (like 89-year-old Frederick Carrier, seen in this picture) -- are not forgotten.

Photo by Sean Gallup/Getty Images.

How do you beat the heat? 

Perhaps you should do like koalas do and hug a tree. Before you knock it, there's science behind it - researchers discovered that koalas hug the lower parts of trees because that's where it's cooler. http://bit.ly/1odxEyy

Let's all give the koalas a 'like' for being smart and completely adorable at the same time.
